{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}
[[File:Alfred Butt Vanity Fair 21 December 1910.jpg|thumb|right|<center>"[[Palace Theatre, London|The Palace]]"<br>Butt as caricatured in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], December 1910</center>]]
'''Sir Alfred Butt, 1st Baronet'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p23533.htm|title=Person Page #235325| publisher=Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes, Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.:, 2003, volume 1, page 450. Genealogical Books Ltd, 2003|accessdate=2014-11-24}}</ref> (20 March 1878 – 8 December 1962) was a British theatre impresario, [[Conservative party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and racehorse owner and breeder. During a fourteen-year tenure as manager of [[London]]'s [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]], beginning in 1904, Butt built a theatre empire, expanding firstly with the [[Alhambra Theatre Glasgow|Alhambra Theatre]], [[Glasgow]] in 1910, followed by the London Victoria Palace a year later, to rival that of Edward Moss and others. He became managing director of several London West End theatres beginning in 1914, including the [[Adelphi Theatre]], the [[Empire, Leicester Square|Empire Theatre]], the [[Gaiety Theatre, London|Gaiety Theatre]] and the [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]], as well as theatres outside London. He continued as a theatre impresario until 1931.

During the [[First World War]], also, Butt became Director of Food Rationing at the [[Minister of Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Food]]. He was [[knight bachelor|knighted]] for his services to the ministry, and for his work for war charities, in 1918. He was elected as Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Balham and Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Balham and Tooting]] in 1922. In 1929, he was created a [[Butt baronets|baronet "of Westminster in the County of London"]] for his services to political and public life. He was forced to resign from the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|Commons]] in June 1936 over a financial scandal. After this, Butt concentrated on horse racing.<ref name=odnb>{{cite web | title=Butt, Sir Alfred | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/56176 | work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2004 | accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref>

==Life and career==
Alfred Butt was born in London, the son of solicitor [[Solomon Beyfus (1820-1893)#Alfred Butt|Alfred Beyfus]] whose forebears had migrated from [[Hamburg]] to Glasgow and London, and educated at [[Emanuel School]] before entering employment in the counting-house of [[Harrod's]] department store where his uncle, [[Edgar Israel Cohen|Edgar Cohen]], through the Beyfus family was a director.<ref name="Smith, Alhambra Glasgow">Smith, ''Alhambra Glasgow''</ref><ref name=odnb/><ref name=obit>{{cite news |title=Obituary: Sir Alfred Butt. Politics, Racing and the Theatre |work=[[The Times]] |page=14 |date=10 December 1962 }}</ref> He subsequently joined the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]], a [[music hall]] in [[Cambridge Circus, London|Cambridge Circus]], London, largely controlled by the Beyfus family and associates.<ref name="Smith, Alhambra Glasgow"/><ref name=odnb/><ref name=obit/> He became company secretary of the Palace Theatre Limited in 1898, at the young age of 19. He quickly advanced to the position of assistant manager, and when [[Charles Morton (impresario)|Charles Morton]] died in 1904, he became manager of the Palace. In 1906 he became managing director, a position he held for 14 years.<ref name=odnb/><ref name=obit/>

He developed close links with the [[Orpheum Circuit|Orpheum Vaudeville Circuit]] and its associates in the United States, and brought numerous American stars to London. He also introduced British audiences to continental performers such as [[Anna Pavlova]] and [[Yvette Guilbert]].<ref name=odnb/> In 1910 he greatly expanded his theatre business when he took control of [[Thomas Barrasford]]'s music halls and formed a joint company, the "Variety Theatres Controlling Company Limited", with [[Walter de Frece]]. VTCC became the second largest chain of music halls in the United Kingdom, second only to [[Moss Empires]].<ref name=odnb/> Among their London theatres managed by Butt were the Globe and [[Queen's Theatre]]s.<ref name=obit/>

Outside London Butt opened two new theatres, firstly, the [[Alhambra Theatre Glasgow|Alhambra Theatre]], Glasgow, in 1910, designed by [[John James Burnet|Sir John James Burnet]] and, secondly, the [[Theatre Mogador]], [[Paris]] in 1919 (delayed by the [[First World War]]), designed by [[Bertie Crewe]].<ref name=obit/> Butt became managing director of three West End theatres during the war: the [[Adelphi Theatre]] (1915–19), the [[Empire, Leicester Square|Empire Theatre]] (1914–28) and the [[Gaiety Theatre, London|Gaiety Theatre]] (1915–19). He became joint owner and managing director of London's [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]] from 1925-31.<ref name=odnb/><ref name=obit/>

Also during the First World War, he was appointed in 1917 by the new Prime Minister [[David Lloyd George]], on the recommendation of Lord Northcote, as the Director of Food Rationing and introduced compulsory food rationing with the support of his principal civil servant [[William Beveridge]].<ref name="Smith, Alhambra Glasgow"/> He was [[knight bachelor|knighted]] for his services to the Ministry, and for his work for war charities, in 1918.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30825 |date=2 August 1918 |page=9111}}</ref><ref name=odnb/><ref name=obit/>

Butt was a supporter of the Conservative & Unionist Party. After standing unsuccessfully for the party at parliamentary elections at [[Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]] and [[Paddington North (UK Parliament constituency)|Paddington North]], he was elected as member of parliament for [[Balham and Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Balham and Tooting]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1922|1922 general election]].<ref name=odnb/><ref name=obit/> In 1929 he was created a [[Butt baronets|baronet "of Westminster in the County of London"]] for his services to political and public life.<ref name=odnb/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33523 |date=6 August 1929 |page=5143 }}</ref> He held the seat at successive elections until he was forced to resign from the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|Commons]] in June 1936 over a scandal concerning a leak of budget details from which he was believed to have benefitted financially.<ref name=odnb/><ref>{{cite news |title=Likely Candidates at Balham |work=[[The Times]] |page=16 |date=13 June 1936}}</ref>

With the end of his political career, Butt concentrated on his interest in the horse-racing industry. He purchased the Brook Stud near [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]]. His two most successful horses were ''[[Steady Aim]]'', winner of [[Epsom Oaks|The Oaks]], and ''[[Petition (horse)|Petition]]'', winner of the [[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|Ascot New Stakes]], both in 1946.<ref name=odnb/>

==Personal life==
He was married twice. The first marriage in 1908 was to Georgina Mary Say, who died in 1960. His second marriage was to Wilhelmine Wahl later in 1960. He had one son, Kenneth Dudley Butt, from his first marriage.

Sir Alfred Butt died at his Newmarket home in December 1962, aged 84.<ref name=obit/> He was cremated at [[Cambridge]] Crematorium.<ref name=odnb/>

