{{short description|Nickname for Nine of Diamonds playing card}}
{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}
[[File:Playing card diamond 9.svg|thumb|upright|right|The '''Nine of Diamonds''' is sometimes referred to as the '''Curse of Scotland'''.]]
The '''Curse of Scotland''' is a nickname used for the '''Nine of Diamonds''' [[playing card]].<ref name=mw>{{cite book|title=Merriam-Webster Unabridged Dictionary|publisher=Merriam-Webster.com.|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/curse%20of%20Scotland|accessdate=23 April 2014|chapter=Curse of Scotland}}<br>The Oxford English Dictionary (1971) and Chambers 20th Century Dictionary (1983) give similar definitions</ref> The expression has been used at least since the early 18th century, and many putative explanations have been given for the origin of this [[List of playing-card nicknames#endnote 9h|nickname for the card]].

==Earliest printed references==
[[File:Curse of Scotland.png|thumb|right|upright|Extract from ''British Apollo'' of 1708]]
In a book printed in London in 1708, ''The British Apollo, or, Curious amusements for the ingenious'', a question is posed:

<blockquote>Q. ''Why is the'' Nine of Diamonds ''called'' the curse of Scotland?<br/>
A. Diamonds as the Ornamental Jewels of a Regnal Crown, imply no more in the above-nam'd Proverb than a mark of Royalty, for SCOTLAND'S ''Kings'' for many Ages, were observ'd, each ''Ninth'' to be a ''Tyrant'', who by Civil Wars, and all the fatal consequences of [[wikt:intestine|intestine]] discord, plunging the ''Divided Kingdom'' into strange Disorders, gave occasion, ''in the course of time'', to form the Proverb.<ref name=bp1708>{{cite book|last=A Society of Gentlemen|title=The British Apollo, or, Curious amusements for the ingenious, Volume I|date=13 February 1708|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gRYTAAAAQAAJ&pg=PT225#v=onepage&q&f=false}}. See also {{cite web|title=Dictionary of the Scottish language|url=http://www.dsl.ac.uk/getent4.php?plen=1885&startset=8129577&dtext=snd&query=CURSE_OF_SCOTLAND|publisher=Scottish Language Dictionaries|accessdate=23 April 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424125356/http://www.dsl.ac.uk/getent4.php?plen=1885&startset=8129577&dtext=snd&query=CURSE_OF_SCOTLAND|archivedate=24 April 2014|df=dmy-all}} (entry for ''Curse of Scotland'').</ref></blockquote>

A similar book of 1726 gives the same question and answer, still regarding the question as relating to a proverb.<ref name=apollo>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Theodore|title=The British Apollo: Containing Two Thousand Answers to Curious. Volume 2|date=1726|publisher=Arthur Bettesworth|page=533|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wHo0AAAAMAAJ&dq=%22british%20apollo%22%20%22curse%20of%20scotland%22&pg=PA533#v=onepage&q=%22british%20apollo%22%20%22curse%20of%20scotland%22&f=false|edition=3rd}}</ref> By 1757 the card was described as "commonly called the Curse of Scotland" with the explanation that the epithet refers to [[Adam Cockburn, Lord Ormiston|Lord Ormistoune]], [[Lord Justice Clerk]] from 1692 to 1735, who suppressed the [[Jacobite rising of 1715]] and "became universally hated in Scotland".<ref>{{cite web|title=Dictionary of the Scottish language|url=http://www.dsl.ac.uk/getent4.php?plen=45582&startset=23730321&query=LORD&fhit=curse+of+scotland&dregion=entry&dtext=snd#fhit|publisher=Scottish Language Dictionaries|accessdate=23 April 2014}} (entry for ''Lord'')</ref> In 18th-century Scotland, the nine of diamonds was sometimes called the "Justice Clerk", and was considered to be the most unlucky card in the pack.<ref name=Burnett>{{cite web|last=Burnett|first=Peter|title=The Curse of Scotland Part 1|url=http://peterburnett.info/scotland-blog/665-the-curse-of-scotland-pt-1|publisher=peterburnett.info|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref>

=="Pope Joan" and 19th century speculation==
James Mitchell's 1825 ''Scotsman's Library'' claimed that the expression originated from the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]] writing orders on such a card before the [[Battle of Bothwell Bridge]] (1679).<ref name=mitchell>{{cite book|last=Mitchell|first=James|title=The Scotsman's Library; Being a Collection of Anecdotes and Facts Illustrative of Scotland and Scotsmen|date=1825|publisher=Anderson, Cumming & Jones|location=London|page=600|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UVtZAAAAcAAJ&lpg=PA600&ots=ZZYkwuqj0k&dq=Duke%20of%20Monmouth%20before%20the%20battle%20of%20Bothwell%20Brig%20nine%20diamonds&pg=PA600#v=snippet&q=nine%20diamonds&f=false}}</ref>
Despite this, in ''[[The Spectator]]'', a reviewer of an 1885 book by George Gomme<ref name=gomme>{{cite book|last=Gomme|first=George Lawrence|title=The "Gentleman's Magazine Library: being a classified collection of the chief contents of the Gentleman's Magazine from 1731 to 1868;|date=1884|location=London|url=http://ebook.lib.hku.hk/CADAL/B31402793/}}</ref> commented that the reviewer had believed that the phrase had started from an order written on a {{diamonds}}9 by the [[Prince William, Duke of Cumberland|Duke of Cumberland]] ("Butcher" Cumberland) on the eve of the [[Battle of Culloden]] (1746). However he went on to remark that the book claims that "The curse of Scotland must be something which that nation hates and detests. The Scots held in the utmost detestation the Pope."<ref name=spectator />{{refn|group=note|The pope was sometimes known to [[Presbyterianism#Scotland|Scots presbyterians]] as the [[antichrist]].<ref name=scotsman>{{cite news|title=Is the Curse of Scotland in the cards?|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/is-the-curse-of-scotland-in-the-cards-1-466324|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=9 March 2006|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424124418/http://www.scotsman.com/news/is-the-curse-of-scotland-in-the-cards-1-466324|archivedate=24 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}

[[File:Lady Godina's rout; - or - Peeping-Tom spying out Pope-Joan by James Gillray.jpg|thumb|left|[[James Gillray]] caricature of 1796 showing a lady playing ''Pope Joan'' and holding the nine of diamonds]]
In the card game [[Pope Joan (card game)|Pope Joan]], very popular in the 19th century, the {{diamonds}}9 is the most powerful card, and it is called the "Pope". The game is played on a special board on which the middle is marked "Pope Joan", and it is used in association with this card. The game uses 51 cards (the {{diamonds}}8 is excluded, making the {{diamonds}}7, later called the "[[beer card]]", a "stop") but there is no direct relation with the {{diamonds}}9.<ref name=trussel>{{cite web|last=Trussel|first=Steve|title=Pope-Joan|url=http://www.trussel.com/maig/pope.htm|work=EclectiCity|publisher=trussel.com|accessdate=24 April 2014}} quoting Encyclopædia Britannica, 11th edition</ref> Gomme's book goes on to claim "At the game of Pope Joan, the nine of diamonds is Pope; therefore the nine of diamonds is the curse of Scotland". ''The Spectator'' review considered the claim "more cogent in form than in matter".<ref name=spectator>{{cite journal|title=Papers from the "Gentleman's Magazine"|journal=The Spectator|date=14 March 1885|page=357|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/14th-march-1885/17/papers-from-the-gentlemans-magazine|accessdate=23 April 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424124403/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/14th-march-1885/17/papers-from-the-gentlemans-magazine|archivedate=24 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

[[File:Earl of Stair COA.svg|thumb|upright|right|Arms of the Earl of Stair. The Dalrymple family arms are in the upper right [[Quartering (heraldry)|quarter]] (as seen from behind the shield)]]
A letter written in response to ''The Spectator's'' book review pointed out that the saying was established well before Culloden, and preferred the Pope Joan theory to other explanations.<ref name=black />

Other explanations given in the letter were:
* the family arms of [[John Dalrymple, 1st Earl of Stair|John Dalrymple, Earl of Stair]] (the villain of the [[massacre of Glencoe]]) have a more than passing resemblance to the {{diamonds}}9 playing card;
[[File:Flag of Scotland (traditional).svg|thumb|St Andrew's Cross]]
* "curse" is a corruption of "cross" and the nine pips on cards were in the form of a [[Flag of Scotland|St Andrew's Cross]];
* a thief in [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]' reign attempted to steal the Crown Jewels and got away with nine diamonds, and all Scotland was taxed for the theft;{{refn|group=note|The thief was one George Campbell.<ref name=scotsman />}}
* [[James IV]], before the [[Battle of Flodden]], spent time searching for a missing card—the {{diamonds}}9—time which would have been better spent in preparing for the battle;
* [[Mary of Lorraine]] (or maybe [[James, Duke of York]]) introduced the game of "Comette" into Scotland, in which the {{diamonds}}9 is the winning card, against which many Scottish nobles lost their wealth.<ref name=black>{{cite journal|last=Black|first=William George|title=The Curse of scotland|journal=The Spectator|date=21 March 1887|page=387|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/21st-march-1885/15/the-curse-of-scotland|accessdate=23 April 2014}} (The Spectator originally misprinted the author's surname)</ref>{{refn|group=note|Many of the claims had been previously published in Chambers' ''The Book of Days'' (1864).<ref name=chambers>{{cite book
|last = Chambers|first = Robert|authorlink = Robert Chambers (publisher born 1802)|title = The Book of Days: A Miscellany of Popular Antiquities in Connection with the Calendar, Including Anecdote, Biography, & History, Curiosities of Literature and Oddities of Human Life and Character, Vol I|publisher = W & R Chambers|year=1864|page=75|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=q24oAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+book+of+days#PPA75,M1}}</ref>}}

An 1864 book by [[Robert Chambers (publisher born 1802)|Robert Chambers]], upon which this letter seems to have been based, describes the theories as "most lame and unsatisfactory suggestions" compared with the Dalrymple theory. The book dismisses the Culloden theory because of an earlier 1745 caricature of "the young chavalier attempting to lead a herd of bulls, laden with papal curses, excommunications &c., across the Tweed, with the Nine of Diamonds lying before them".<ref name=chambers />

==More recent opinion==
In the 1898 edition of ''[[Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and Fable]]'' the "Pope Joan" and "Comette" theories are favoured although many of the others are listed – more recent editions venture no opinion.<ref name=brewer1>{{cite book|last=Brewer|first=E. Cobham|title=Dictionary of Phrase and Fable|date=1898|url=http://www.bartleby.com/81/4502.html}}</ref><ref name=brewer2>{{cite book|last=Brewer|first=E. Cobham|title=Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and fable|date=1959|publisher=Cassell Publications|isbn=0304340049|edition=14th|editor=Ivor H. Evans}}</ref> In [[William Gurney Benham|Gurney Benham's]] book about playing cards, in describing the game of Pope Joan he gives his own explanation for why this card is known as the Curse of Scotland: "The crown of Scotland contained only nine stones, as they never could afford a tenth".<ref name=parlett>{{cite web|last=Parlett|first=David|title=Pope Joan: The "Curse of Scotland" game|work=Parlett's Historic Card games|url=http://www.parlettgames.uk/histocs/popejoan.html|series=Historic Card Games|df=dmy-all}} quoting {{cite book|last=Benhan|first=W. Gurney|authorlink=William Gurney Benham|title=Playing Cards: A History of the Pack and Explanations of its Many Secrets|date=1931|location=London}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|In quoting this, Parlett regards this suggestion as "perhaps the most amusing".<ref name=parlett />}} [[Eric Partridge]]'s ''Routledge Dictionary of Historical Slang'' considers: “the various theories are as interesting as they are unconvincing”.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Paul|title=The Curse of Scotland|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/history/the_curse_of_scotland.shtml|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 April 2014|date=17 February 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816074751/http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/history/the_curse_of_scotland.shtml|archivedate=16 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Collins Encyclopedia of Scotland]]'' says for ''Curse of Scotland'' "This is usually taken to be the nine of diamonds playing card, though explanations differ".<ref name=ceos>{{cite book|last1=Keay|first1=John|last2=Keay|authorlink=John Keay|first2=Julia|title=[[Collins Encyclopedia of Scotland]]|date=1994|publisher=harper Collins|isbn=0002550822}}</ref>

==Other connotations==
===Nine of diamonds===
The 19th century [[Tarot of Marseilles]] is one of the standard designs for [[tarot]] cards. It contains a [[The Hierophant|"Pope" card]] (and, indeed, a [[The High Priestess|"Popess"]]) but there seems to be no connection with the Pope Joan card game, even though the popess may have derived from the mythical [[Pope Joan]].<ref name=pardoe>{{cite book|last1=Pardoe|first1=Rosemary A.|last2=Pardoe|first2=Darroll|title=The Female Pope : the Mystery of Pope Joan: the first complete documentation of the facts behind the legend|date=10 March 1988|publisher=Crucible|location=Wellingborough, England|isbn=9781852740139|url=http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~pardos/PopeJoan8.html|edition=1st|chapter=Chapter 8. Pope Joan and the Tarot|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518094013/http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~pardos/PopeJoan8.html|archivedate=18 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

===Curse of Scotland===
The expression "Curse of Scotland" is sometimes used simply to refer to an occasion of bad luck at cards and can also refer to generally unwanted situations in Scotland, such as swarms of [[midge]]s.<ref name=Reid>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Alistair|title=Curse of Scotland|url=http://www.incallander.co.uk/scottishsongs/curse.htm|publisher=Callender Enterprise|accessdate=24 April 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608014723/http://www.incallander.co.uk/scottishsongs/curse.htm|archivedate=8 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There is a [[theatrical superstition]], sometimes called the ''Scottish curse'', that speaking the name ''Macbeth'' in the theatre brings bad luck. Hence "[[the Scottish Play]]" is used to refer to [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] play.

