{{Infobox film | name = Saputangan | image = Saputangan (1949; obverse; wiki).jpg | image_size = | border = | alt = Pamphlet | caption = Pamphlet | director = [[Fred Young (director)|Fred Young]] | producer = | screenplay = [[Tan Tjoei Hock]] | narrator = | starring ={{plain list| *Chatir Harro *Noorsini *[[Astaman]] }} | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = Bintang Soerabaja | distributor = | released = {{Film date|df=yes|1949|||Dutch East Indies}} | runtime = | country = {{plain list| *[[Dutch East Indies]] *[[Indonesia]] }} | language = Indonesian | budget = | gross = }} '''''Saputangan''''' ([[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] for ''Handkerchief'') is a 1949 romance film from what is now Indonesia.{{efn|The film was released during the [[Indonesian National Revolution]], in which time Indonesia had declared itself independent while the [[Dutch East Indies]] was still formally in existence.}} Directed by [[Fred Young (director)|Fred Young]] and starring Chatir Harro, Noorsini, and [[Astaman]], it follows a young doctor who, after his fiancée is blinded in an automobile accident, becomes an [[optometrist]] and restores her sight.
==Plot== As a sign of his love, the medical student Hardjono has given his fiancée Karnasih his handkerchief. After Hardjono finishes his final exams, his parents give him a new car, with which Hardjono takes Karnasih on holiday to Mega Mendung, near [[Bogor]]. However, during their excursion the car crashes into a log. Though Hardjono receives only minor injuries, Karnasih is blinded in the accident.
In the weeks afterwards, Karnasih&mdash;hoping to conceal her loss of sight and thus preserve his love for her&mdash;refuses to meet with Hardjono. Undaunted, Hardjono continues to contact her. When they do meet, Karnasih pretends that she can still see, a ruse which fails after Hardjono attempts to give her a handkerchief which has fallen to the ground.
Hardjono, hoping to become an [[optometrist]] and restore Karnasih's vision, decides to go abroad and receive further training. Karnasih, meanwhile, dedicates her time to educating poor children at her own school, the Taman Karnasih.
Six years pass, and Hardjono&mdash;having received the training he sought&mdash;returns. He operates on Karnasih. Six weeks pass, and Karnasih's vision is restored, allowing her to see her beloved again.{{sfn|Bintang Soerabaja, Saputangan|loc=Reverse}}
==Production== ''Saputangan'' was directed by [[Fred Young (director)|Fred Young]] as the second film for his company Bintang Soerabaja, following ''Sehidup Semati'' (''One in Life, One in Death'').{{sfn|Biran|2009a|p=368}} Young initially wrote the story as a stage play for his theatrical troupe, also named Bintang Soerabaja.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Saputangan}}{{sfn|''De Vrie Pers'', Indonesische film}} The story was adapted into a screenplay by [[Tan Tjoei Hock]],{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Saputangan}} who had joined the company together with financier and film producer [[The Teng Chun]].{{sfn|Biran|2009b|p=58}} Production began in September 1949 and was, at the time, estimated to require two months of filming.{{sfn|''De Vrie Pers'', Indonesische film}}
Though the film was shot in [[black-and-white]], the titular handkerchiefs in ''Saputangan'' were [[Film colorization|hand-tinted]]. The Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] writes that this hand tinting, done owing to references to the handkerchiefs' colour, was done poorly, such that the colour was jittery.{{sfn|Biran|2009a|p=368}}
[[File:Scene from Saputangan 5 (pamphlet; obverse).jpg|thumb|A scene from the film]] The film starred Chatir Harro, Noorsini, and [[Astaman]]. It also featured [[Netty Herawaty]], [[Darussalam (actor)|Darussalam]], Ribut Rawit, Mohammad Jusuf, Sukarsih, R.A. Sri Mulat, Pak Kasur, and [[Lilik Sudjio]].{{sfn|Bintang Soerabaja, Saputangan|loc=Obverse}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Saputangan}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Lilik Sudjio}} Its soundtrack featured seven songs, including "Inilah Laguku" ("This is My Song"), "Asmara Kelana" ("Love of the Wanderer"), "Saputangan" ("Handkerchief"), "Pulau Bali" ("The Island of Bali"), and "Saputangan Tanda Kasih" ("Handkerchief, Sign of Love").{{sfn|Bintang Soerabaja, Saputangan|loc=Obverse and Reverse}}{{sfn|Biran|2009a|p=368}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Saputangan}}
==Release and reception== A novelisation of ''Saputangan'' was published by Gapura in 1949; the publishing house, owned by [[Andjar Asmara]], had novelised all Indonesian films produced or in production since independence up to that point.{{sfn|''Java Bode'', Gapura}} The film was in theatres by February 1950, when it was screening in [[Jakarta]].{{sfn|''Java Bode'', Waar Gaan We Heen?}} The film was exported to [[Singapore]], where it was banned by the film censor Jack Evans in May 1950 for being "not up to standards";{{sfn|Behague|1950|p=17}} J. B. Kristanto, in his ''[[Katalog Film Indonesia]]'' (''Indonesian Film Catalogue''), suggests that the issue was [[Communism]]-inspired dialogue.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Saputangan}} This ban was lifted on 1 June 1950,{{sfn|''The Straits Times'', Censor's Ban}} and ''Saputangan'' was soon screened to popular success at the Alhambra Theatre.{{Sfn|''The Straits Times'', 'Three Came Home'}}
The reviewer for the ''Sunday Courier'' received ''Saputangan'' warmly, writing that the film was "unlike any other"{{efn|Original: "''Laen daripada jang laen.''"}} and was the first Indonesian film to not feature any fighting.{{sfn|Biran|2009a|p=368}}
''Saputangan'' may now be [[lost film|lost]]. Movies in the Indies were recorded on highly flammable [[nitrate film]], and after a fire destroyed much of [[Produksi Film Negara]]'s warehouse in 1952, old films shot on nitrate were deliberately destroyed.{{sfn|Biran|2012|p=291}} The American visual anthropologist [[Karl G. Heider]] writes that all Indonesian films from before 1950 are lost.{{sfn|Heider|1991|p=14}} However, Kristanto records several as having survived at [[Sinematek Indonesia]]'s archives, and Biran writes that several Japanese propaganda films have survived at the [[Netherlands Government Information Service]].{{sfn|Biran|2009a|p=351}}
